items.title: Wahlenbergia luteola
items.content_text: Lots of plants flowering inside and outside of a burnt area. Flowers lacked yellow colouring on the underside of petals, usually a key feature of W. luteola, but the leaves are all opposite, a feature that separates luteola from communis.

items.title: Solenogyne dominii
items.content_text: All plants seemed to have flower stems. The area had undergone a controlled burn.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Looks a bit like Lamarckia aurea but I don't think it is. Only one plant seen.

items.title: Arthropodium sp. 3 (aff. strictum)
items.content_text: Showing 2 flowers per node.

items.title: Disa bracteata
items.content_text: 2 plants at this location.

items.title: Stackhousia subterranea
items.content_text: Pics show the four ID features of unbranched flower stem, thickish leathery leaves, spreads by rhizomes forming 'patches', swollen sac at base of bract.

items.title: Stackhousia subterranea
items.content_text: Showing swollen base of bract that is characteristic of this species compared to S. monogyna (cf. 10039).

items.title: Eutaxia microphylla var. microphylla
items.content_text: The for is a prostrate groundcover here at Evans Street.

items.title: Petrorhagia dubia
items.content_text: 3rd pic shows ID features. 1) Densely glandular-tomentose mid-stem between leaf nodes. 2) Leaf sheath twice as long as stem width. 3) Seed tuberculate, 1-1.3mm (0.5mm marks on ruler in pic).

items.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. angustissimus
items.content_text: Distinctive leaves on this subspecies. I was once told they are sometimes seen growing with subsp. omnigracilis and they are obviously different when seen together. It is true. See also obs 7616.

items.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. omnigracilis
items.content_text: omnigracilis means 'all bits' slender, referring to the thin lobes on all leaves.

items.title: Dillwynia cinerascens s.s.
items.content_text: A very large, grey form.

items.title: Geranium sp. 3
items.content_text: 1st pic shows blue-purple dehiscence lines on anthers. 2nd pic show broad lobed over-winter leaf (bottom - seems to have spreading hairs) & thin-dissected summer leaves (top left). Peduncle seems to have appressed hairs.

items.title: Romulea rosea var. australis s.s.
items.content_text: Camera doesn't show colour well, which was very deep pink, almost magenta. Leaves diamond-shaped in cross-section and 2mm wide making it var. australis.

items.title: Stackhousia subterranea
items.content_text: Spider lurking behind the flower has just caught an insect.

items.title: Geranium retrorsum s.s.
items.content_text: Geranium retrorsum dominates away from the rocky knoll. The white-flowered Geranium sp.3 dominates on the slopes of the rocky knoll - see observation 6593.

items.title: Geranium sp. 3
items.content_text: Geranium sp. 3 seems to dominate on the slopes of the rocky knoll. The pink-flowered Geranium retrorsum dominates away from the slope - see observation 6594.

items.title: Romulea minutiflora
items.content_text: A few plants among thousands of Romulea rosea.

items.title: Drosera aberrans
items.content_text: Good displays on the slope of the rocky knoll.

items.title: Pauridia glabella var. glabella
items.content_text: Flower about 8mm across. IDed by pair of non-sheathing bracteoles.

items.title: Wurmbea latifolia subsp. vanessae
items.content_text: Almost impossible to spot, being only the odd plant among the thousands of Romulea weeds everywhere.

items.title: Disa bracteata
items.content_text: This and other plants removed by Hume Council staff.

items.title: Arthropodium sp. 3 (aff. strictum)
items.content_text: Suspect this is A. sp. 3. Anthers lack yellow appendages and I can see at least one node with two flowers.
